<div class="prose">
  <h1>Projects</h1>
  <p>
    One question — <em>what does it take to be?</em> — pursued at the
    smallest honest scale we can build and hold in a hand.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="projects">
  <article class="project">
    <h3>being.0 <span class="tag">embodiment</span></h3>
    <p>
      The floor of the question, made physical. A small creature — a single
      board, a strip of light, a microphone, soon an eye — that takes its
      hidden internal state and renders it as colour, breathing and shifting
      as it perceives the room. The minimum viable interior, held in the
      hand. What is the least it takes to feel like there's something in
      there?
    </p>
  </article>
</div>

<div class="prose" style="margin-top:2.5rem">
  <h2>Lineage</h2>
  <p>
    The aesthetic owes more to Stanisław Lem than to any AI lab: machines
    worth taking seriously as beings, built and described with rigour and
    affection. The methods borrow from how nervous systems actually
    work — perception, drives, rest, consolidation — rather than from the
    usual vocabulary of the field.
  </p>
</div>
